  "text": "Many studies in the literature have made use of a very simplistic approach in which only two regular HSQC spectra, one of the diamagnetic state and the other of the paramagnetic state at the same concentration, are employed to determine 1 H N -C 2 rates using Eq. (7). We refer to this method as the single-time-point approach. Eq. (7), however, only holds true if the repetition delay is sufficiently long to ensure that magnetization recovery levels are identical for the diamagnetic and paramagnetic states. However, for conventional HSQC experiments on biological macromolecules, the repetition delay between the scans is generally set to 0.8-2.0 s, which is not sufficient for 100% recovery of 1 H longitudinal magnetizations. Indeed, for a 2 H-labeled protein, the amide 1 H-T 1 relaxation time at regular magnetic fields ( 1 H frequency of 500-800 MHz) is very long and a repetition delay longer than $20 s would be required to achieve 100% recovery for all amide 1 H nuclei [CITATION_1] . With a shorter repetition delay, T rep , the recovery levels for the paramagnetic sample are always higher than those for the corresponding diamagnetic sample owing to the PRE on longitudinal relaxation rates (C 1 ). When this effect is taken into account, Eq. (7) is modified to a Calculations were carried out using a Monte-Carlo approach with 100 synthetic datasets as described in the main text. Definitions of symbols are as follows: n, number of time-points; I dia (0), peak intensity at T = 0 for the diamagnetic state; r I , noise standard deviation; DT, interval for linear sampling of T between 0 and (n À 1)DT; r(C 2 ), standard deviation of calculated C 2 . The deviation of the calculated C 2 from the true C 2 was found to be almost same as r(C 2 ). Thus, for these calculations, precision and accuracy are essentially equivalent. Table 2 Impact of increasing time-points with reduced scan accumulations, keeping the overall measurement time constant, on the precision of C 2 measurements a Calculations were carried out in the same manner as for those in Table 1 , except that different values of I dia (0)/r I were employed to simulate a constant overall measurement time in all cases. For example, to acquire 8 points for T, the number of scans should be a fourth of that for a 2 time-point measurement, resulting in a reduction of 2 in S/N ratio. Definitions of symbols are as given in Table 1 . I para ð0Þ ¼ I dia ð0Þ",
